<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-437-141  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 437 141.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  August 22 1990 n1520 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Impact of the megacarts. (Broadcasting) (cost cutting technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hawker, Pat.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK's radio and television industry is placing emphasis on newtechnology that cuts costs in non-program areas.andP;  The move comesat a time when the industry is losing its audience to videos dueto the proliferation of VCR's.andP;  One remedy involves overhaulingtheir systems to allow for the infusion of money into programmingrather than technical and administration costs.andP;  Another remedyinvolves shifting toward computer automation for both productionand transmission in non-programming areas.andP;  Production andtechnical staff do not take lightly the topic of automation,because of the possible excess of skilled employees.andP;  However,there is increasing support from news room staff and videojournalists for new information technology.andP;  BBC, ITN, and Sky arethe among stations that are currently introducing automation intotheir newsrooms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications IndustryCommunications ManagementAutomationBroadcastingCost Reduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>